INSERT INTO `dataset` (`id`, `prediction`, `common_name`, `scientific_name`, `caused_by`, `treatment`) VALUES
(1, 'Disease: Apple Scab', 'Apple Scab', 'Malus Domestica', 'Apple Scab is caused by the fungus Venturia inaequalis. The fungal disease forms pale yellow or olive-green spots on the upper surface of leaves. Dark, velvety spots may appear on lower surface. Severely infected leaves become twisted and puckered and may drop early in summer.', '\r\nPlanting disease resistant varieties is the best way to manage scab.Apples with good resistance include Akane, Chehalis, Liberty, Prima and Tydeman Red.Fungicides like Bonide Captan, wettable sulfur, summer lime sulfur or Spectracide Immunox can be used to manage apple scab.Proper timing of sprays is needed for fungicides to control disease.Postharvest foliage sprays are a very useful supplement to scab control, especially after a season of high scab incidence.'),
(2, 'Disease: Apple Black Rot Canker', 'Apple Black Rot Canker', 'Malus domestica', 'The fungus Botryosphaeria obtusa can cause devastating losses to apples and crabapples over a wide geographical range and in warm humid climates. The fungus is skilled at lurking in dead apple tissue. It commonly colonizes apple limbs that died after fire blight and can enter through variety of wounds-including pruning cuts. This fungus causes reddish brown cankers that are slightly below the level of the healthy bark around it.', 'Remove them by cutting them out or pruning away the affected limbs at least six inches (15 cm.) beyond the wound. Destroy all infected tissue immediately and keep a watchful eye out for new signs of infection. Although general-purpose fungicides, like copper-based sprays and lime sulfur, can be used to control black rot, nothing will improve apple black rot like removing all sources of spores'),
(3, 'Disease: Apple Cedar Rust', 'Apple Cedar Rust', 'Malus domestica', 'Cedar apple rust (Gymnosporangium juniperi-virginianae) is a fungal disease that requires juniper plants to complete its complicated two year life-cycle. Spores overwinter as a reddish-brown gall on young twigs of various juniper species. ', 'Rake up and dispose of fallen leaves and other debris from under trees.Treat most fungal and bacterial diseases with SERENADE Garden.Use Bonide Orchard Spray containing sulfur and pyrethrins for insect attacks and fungal problems.\r\n'),
(4, 'Disease: Arjun Leaf Spot', 'Arjun Leaf Spot', '	\r\nTerminalia arjuna	\r\n\r\n \r\n', '\r\nThis disease is believed to be caused by deficiency of copper. Withering of leaves is observed in young and tender leaves, which show crinkling soon after expansion from the buds.	\r\n\r\n\r\n', '	\r\n1)Proper cultural operations and field sanitation.\r\n\r\n2)Plucking and burning of diseased leaves.\r\n\r\n3)Spray of Carbendazim @ 0.1% or 0.5% Biltox or 0.5% Diathane M-45.\r\n\r\n'),
(5, 'Disease: Bael Chlorosis', 'Bael Chlorosis', 'Aegle marmelos', 'A common cause of chlorosis is a deficiency of iron or manganese, both of which are present but unavailable in high pH soils (pH>7.2). Iron and manganese are needed by plants to form chlorophyll and to complete photosynthesis.\r\n', 'soil application of elemental sulfur combined with ferrous (iron) sulfate,iron chelates; foliar sprays containing ferrous sulfate or chelated iron; or trunk injection of ferric ammonium citrate or iron sulfate'),
(6, 'Disease: Black Plum Anthracnose', 'Black Plum Anthracnose', 'Syzygiumc umini', '	\r\nAnthracnose disease is induced by the fungus Colletotrichum lagenarium.\r\nAnthracnose generally appears first as small, irregular yellow or brown spots. These spots darken as they age and may also expand, covering the leaves.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '\r\n\r\nPrune out all infected branches in late winter and destroy them by burning, burying, or throwing them away. Remove at least 3-4 inches of healthy tissue below each knot to ensure elimination of the fungus\r\n'),
(7, 'Disease: Blackboard Foliar Galls', 'Blackboard Foliar Galls', 'Alstonia scholaris', 'Morphological, Anatomical and Biochemical alterations in foliar galls of Alstonia scholaris R. Br. induced by the insect Pauropsyllatuberculata (Psyllidae)', 'Prune and destroy gall-infested twigs and branches. Burn or step on the galls to kill the developing larvae. Place gall remains in a tightly sealed baggie or trash bag and discard immediately. Rake and destroy gall-infested fallen leaves.'),
(8, 'Disease: Broccoli Clubroot', 'Broccoli Clubroot', 'Brassica oleracea', 'Clubroot is caused by the pathogen Plasmodiophora brassicae. It affects plants of the brassica family which includes broccoli, broccolini, cauliflower, cabbage, Chinese cabbage, turnips and Brussels sprouts as well as weeds such as wild radish and wild turnip.', 'Plant the broccoli in well-drained soil only. And If you have clay soil with poor drainage, improve it by adding organic matter.Check the soil pH and maintain a soil pH of 6.8 or higher, which can help prevent clubroot.'),
(9, 'Disease: Cherry Powdery Mildew', 'Cherry Powdery Mildew', 'Prunus avium', 'Powdery mildew of sweet and sour cherry is caused by Podosphaera clandestina, an obligate biotrophic fungus. Mid- and late-season sweet cherry (Prunus avium) cultivars are commonly affected, rendering them unmarketable due to the covering of white fungal growth on the cherry surface ', 'Spray on plants every one to two weeks. Potassium bicarbonate– Similar to baking soda, this has the unique advantage of actually eliminating powdery mildew. Potassium bicarbonate is a contact fungicide which kills the powdery mildew spores quickly.'),
(10, 'Disease: Chinar Leaf Spot', 'Chinar Leaf Spot', 'Platanus orientalis', 'A leaf spot is a limited, discoloured, diseased area of a leaf that is caused by fungal, bacterial or viral plant diseases, or by injuries from nematodes, insects, environmental factors, toxicity or herbicides. These discoloured spots or lesions often have a centre of necrosis or cell death', 'Traditional treatment by spraying with a mild solution of bicarbonate of soda (baking soda), using ½ teaspoon per gallon (2.5mL per 4L) of water. Safer-Brand Garden Fungicide can kill existing leaf spot and control the future outbreaks. Remove infected leaves and dead twigs and the remainder of the plant can be treated to prevent further damage, using a copper fungicide.'),
(11, 'Disease: Chinese Cabbage Fusarium Wilt', 'Chinese Cabbage Fusarium Wilt', 'Brassica rapa subsp. pekinensis', 'Fusarium wilt, widespread plant disease caused by many forms of the soil-inhabiting fungus Fusarium oxysporum', 'Remove and dispose of affected plants immediately, Whenever possible, remove and replace fusarium-infected garden soil. Mycostop is a biological fungicide that will safely protect crops against wilt caused by Fusarium.'),
(12, 'Disease: Corn Cercospora Leaf Spot', 'Corn Cercospora Leaf Spot', 'Zea mays	\r\n\r\n', 'The gray leaf spot disease is caused by the fungus Cercospora zeae-maydis. It survives in plant residues in the soil for long periods of time. During the spring, the spores are carried onto the lower leaves by rain splashes and wind.', 'Destroy infected crop residue from the field. Use of resistant/tolerant hybrids. Foliar spray of Mancozeb @ 2.5 g/ L of water after about 15 days after sowing is effective and provide two more sprays at 10-day intervals or immediately after symptoms appearance.\r\n'),
(13, 'Disease: Corn Common Rust', 'Corn Common Rust', 'Zea mays	\r\n\r\n', 'The disease is caused by the fungus Puccinia sorghi. The fungus overwinters in an alternate host (a species of Oxalis) and releases spores during the spring. The spores can be transported over great distances by winds and rain.', 'If the corn begins to show symptoms of infection, immediately spray with a fungicide. Products containig mancozeb, pyraclostrobin + fluxapyroxad, azoxystrobin + propiconazole, trifloxystrobin + prothioconazole can be used to control the disease.'),
(14, 'Disease: Corn Leaf Blight', 'Corn Leaf Blight', 'Zea mays', 'corn leaf blight (CLB) or Turcicum leaf blight (TLB) is a foliar disease of corn (maize) caused by Exserohilum turcicum, the anamorph of the ascomycete Setosphaeria turcica. With its characteristic cigar-shaped lesions, this disease can cause significant yield loss in susceptible corn hybrids.', 'Plant corn with enough space for airflow and water in the morning so leaves can dry throughout the day. Foliar fungicides may be applied early in the growing season to corn seedlings as a risk-management tool for corn leaf blight. Combination of rotating away from corn for one year followed by tillage is recommended to prevent leaf blight.'),
(15, 'Disease: Cucumber Bacterial Wilt', 'Cucumber Bacterial Wilt', 'Cucumis sativus', 'Cucumber bacterial wilt is caused by the bacterium, Erwinia tracheiphila, and is characterized initially by wilting and drying of individual leaves, especially those exhibiting cucumber beetle injury.', 'Protect plants with netting. Remove and destroy plant material when symptoms of wilting are first noticed. Grow susceptible crops on rotation every third year. Grow varieties that tolerate bacterial wilt like butternut or acorn squash and Saladin or County Fair 83 cucumbers. Dust plants with insecticide in the spring before the cucumber beetles have a chance to lay eggs.\r\n'),
